body_raw:
Is it possible to construct a bijection $F:\mathbb Z 	o \mathbb Z$ without fixed points (i.e. such that $F(i)
eq i$ for all $i \in \mathbb Z$ ) such that for all $j\in\mathbb Z_{
eq 0}$ , $$\lim_{n	o \infty}  rac{1}{n}\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}F(jk)-jk=0?$$ For the moment I'm just able to do the following observation: Since $F(jk)-jk
eq 0$ for all $j\in\mathbb Z_{
eq 0}, k\in \mathbb{Z}_{\geq 0}$ , then for every fixed $j \in \mathbb Z_{
eq 0}$ there must be infinitely many $k\geq 0$ s.t. $F(jk)-jk>0$ and infinitely many $k\geq 0$ s.t. $F(jk)-jk<0$ . This, in my mind, implies that $F$ has to be "really chaotic" and at the moment I do not know how to construct such a bijection. Any idea? Any help?

